# RTL Design & Synthesis Workshop

A hands-on internship covering Verilog RTL design, logic synthesis, and flop coding styles using open-source EDA tools.

---

## Table of Contents

- [Module 1 – Introduction to Verilog RTL Design & Synthesis](#module-1)
- [Module 2 – Timing Libs, Hierarchical vs Flat Synthesis & Flop Coding Styles](#module-2)

---

## Module 1 – Introduction to Verilog RTL Design & Synthesis <a name="module-1"></a>

### Step 1 – Setting up iverilog

Install and initialise the open-source Icarus Verilog simulator.

```bash
sudo apt install iverilog gtkwave
```

Write a Verilog source file and a testbench, then compile and simulate:

```bash
iverilog -o sim design.v testbench.v
./sim
```

![iverilog simulation](internship/task1.png)

---

### Step 2 – Viewing waveforms with GTKWave

Dump a `.vcd` file from your testbench and open it in GTKWave to inspect signal transitions.

```bash
gtkwave dump.vcd
```

![GTKWave waveform](internship/task2gtkwave.png)

---

### Step 3 – Logic Synthesis with Yosys

Launch Yosys and read in the design along with the Sky130 standard-cell library.

```bash
yosys
> read_liberty -lib sky130_fd_sc_hd__tt_025C_1v80.lib
> read_verilog good_mux.v
> synth -top good_mux
```

![Yosys initialisation](internship/yosysinitialisation.png)

---

### Step 4 – Mapping and generating a netlist

Run ABC to map the synthesised design to standard cells, then write and view the netlist.

```bash
> abc -liberty sky130_fd_sc_hd__tt_025C_1v80.lib
> show
> write_verilog -noattr netlist.v
```

![Synthesised netlist](internship/generated_netlist.png)  
![Corrected schematic](internship/corrected_sch.png)

---

### Step 5 – Labs using Yosys and Sky130 PDKs

Verify that the synthesised netlist matches the RTL simulation by re-running the testbench against the generated netlist.

![Input/output verification](internship/inputandoutputyosys.png)

---

## Module 2 – Timing Libs, Hierarchical vs Flat Synthesis & Flop Coding Styles <a name="module-2"></a>

### Step 6 – Exploring timing libraries

Open the Sky130 `.lib` file and understand cell attributes: drive strength, timing arcs, and power.

---

### Step 7 – Hierarchical vs Flat Synthesis

Synthesise a multi-module design and compare the two views.

**Hierarchical** – sub-module boundaries are preserved:

```bash
> synth -top multiple_modules
> show multiple_modules
```

![Hierarchy visible](internship/hierarchy_visible.png)

**Flat** – all hierarchy is dissolved into a single netlist:

```bash
> flatten
> show
```

![Flattened netlist](internship/flattened+netlist.png)  
![Flattened schematic](internship/flattened_sch.png)

Sub-module synthesis (useful for large or repeated blocks):

```bash
> synth -top sub_module1
```

![Sub-module synthesis](internship/submodule1.png)

---

### Step 8 – Flop Coding Styles and Optimisation

Simulate and synthesise different D flip-flop variants to see how the tool infers flip-flops.

| Style | Screenshot |
|---|---|
| Async reset | ![](internship/dff_async_rst.png) |
| Async set | ![](internship/dff_async_set.png) |
| Sync reset | ![](internship/dff_syncres.png) |
| Async + sync reset | ![](internship/dff_async_sync.png) |

Synthesised schematics after `dfflibmap`:

```bash
> dfflibmap -liberty sky130_fd_sc_hd__tt_025C_1v80.lib
> abc -liberty sky130_fd_sc_hd__tt_025C_1v80.lib
> show
```

![Async DFF schematic](internship/async_dff.png)  
![Sync-reset DFF schematic](internship/syncres_dff.png)

---

### Step 9 – Special optimisations (mult2, mult8)

Some arithmetic mappings require no standard cells — the tool realises them purely through wiring.

```bash
> synth -top mult2
> abc -liberty sky130_fd_sc_hd__tt_025C_1v80.lib   # reports 0 cells
> show
```

![mult2 netlist](internship/abc_mul2.png)  
![mult8 netlist](internship/abc_mult8.png)

